# Annex 1

**Treatment dispensed to the Memorecord Interviews Resource Collection.** 

  
![](data:image/png;base64,)

The Memorecord Interviews Resource Collection includes video-recorded interviews and PixStories. Most of the video recorded interviews, apart from those made on the spot with the iPhone and/or PixStori app, was done with a Sony Handycam AVCHD Progressive model, generating different files AVCHD files[^footnote-ref-1]\*. These files have been manually assembled in one single video with the same duration of the whole interview. Once the video clips of a single interview were assembled, they were uploaded to Memorecord's YouTube Channel. They had the original language caption added on the YouTube Studio, as well as the English translation to non-English speaking interviewees. Captions were created from the transcriptions of the interviews with the timestamps. English translations were also prepared with the timestamps and uploaded as a SubRip subtitle file to Youtube. On Youtube, video descriptions were edited to display different passages separately, according to the time stamps identified in the interview coding, added as the video summary. With the YouTube ID, videos 'were ingested in the Manifold digital publishing platform, under the **Memorecord Interviews Resource Collections** including a short description of the video (with *whom, where, when* it was recorded), the video summary and tags imported from the interviews coding model.

[^footnote-ref-1]: * AVCHD (Advanced Video Coding High Definition) is a file-based format for the digital recording and playback of the high-definition video developed jointly by Sony and Panasonic. An AVCHD file is not a single video file. However, a hierarchical file structure derived from the file structure common to Blu-ray disc, capable of storing several hours of video in high-definition (HDTV 720p and 1080p). One AVCHD file contains multiple video clips. Although it is becoming a ubiquitous video format to the day, Mac OSX does not handle them very well just yet, nor its internal MTS files (short for MPEG Transport Stream, the single video saved in AVCHD format). For this reason, the manual editing of the video clips was made necessary to assemble them in one single publishable file.
